item.title: About Us
item.dc:creator: lvo1988
item.content:encoded: Who are we? We're 5 students from Cal State Fullerton aiming to help California ConServe resources! Saving the planet one small step at a time. What is ConServe? ConServe is an app that will contribute to the resolution of water and energy conservation and waste reduction through a gaming system of goal settings and point accumulation. The gaming function of the app appeals to children and the younger demographic to get them interested in conservation and develop the right habits early on. The functionality of the app will appeal to the adult audience because it tracks cost savings and goal settings. By turning a serious issue into an exciting and rewarding activity, ConServe will allow people to contribute to water and energy conservation, while feeling accountable for their actions, in an enjoyable way! Why ConServe? Conservation and “going green” has become an increasingly popular and important global mindset. As the dangers of global warming and the alarmingly finite amount of resources are becoming more apparent, being environmentally conscious has become more significant than ever.  Our group has created a resource conservation system to improve the continuous challenge of waste management, targeting water and energy conservation, waste reduction, and recycling in California, through the use of a mobile gaming app called ConServe.

item.title: Home Page
item.dc:creator: lvo1988
item.content:encoded:
Conserve Together

We Care About the Environment

The only way forward, if we are going to improve the quality of the environment, is to get everybody involved.

Learn How

Who’s Leading the Charge

These champions are leading the charge to a greener future. Fight your way to the top!

View Leaderboards

You – The People Behind It All

Post your pictures and view photos of the faces behind our conservation initiative.

View Gallery

We Are One

As individuals, we're able to do our part in order to help conserve. Yes we can save a gallon of water here and there or recycle a can or two, but we have strength in numbers. A single can recycled can be vast among thousands of people recycling and likewise a gallon of water reserved by a large group means having enough for the future. We can make a difference. With California’s extreme drought resulting in insufficient water to serve all water-right holders, it is up to us to put all efforts into conserving not just water, but other resources as well such as electricity, paper, and oil to make a better California for our future generations. See Resources

item.title: Conservation Tips
item.dc:creator: lvo1988
item.content:encoded:
Conserve Water

Turn off the faucet while brushing your teeth. You can save 8 gallons a day according to the U.S. EPA. Fix leaky faucets as soon as you can. Install water-saving faucets, toilets, and shower-heads in your home. Take shorter showers Turn off your sprinklers during rainy seasons. Water your lawn and garden early in the morning when it’s cool out - you reduce the amount of water that evaporates

Recycle Waste

Keep a separate trash can for your recyclables. It makes trash day easier! Plant an herb garden at home. Bring your own reusable bags to the grocery store. Use a reusable water bottle - you’ll save money, and reduce waste. Use old rags or t-shirts instead of paper towels to clean your house. Go paperless and pay your bills online.  

Save Electricity

Switch all of your lightbulbs to energy-efficient ones. CFL bulbs will get you the greatest savings. Look for the ‘energy star’ label when purchasing appliances. Switch off your lights when you leave the room or leave the house. Unplug unused chargers and appliances. Air conditioner maintenance will save money and ensure peak efficiency If you have outdoor lights, swap them for solar energy powered lights

Conserve Water

Fix leaky faucets as soon as you can.

Install water-saving faucets, toilets, and shower-heads in your home.

Take shorter showers

Turn off your sprinklers during rainy seasons.

Water your lawn and garden early in the morning when it’s cool out - you reduce the amount of water that evaporates

Plant an herb garden at home.

Bring your own reusable bags to the grocery store.

Use old rags or t-shirts instead of paper towels to clean your house.

Go paperless and pay your bills online.
